post_text:
PTHSD Board News
At the June 16th Board of Education Meeting the Board of Education was proud to honor the careers of retiring staff members and staff members who have served the district for twenty-five years. The Board was also proud to honor all the Parsippany-Troy Hills School Teachers who were named 2020 Teachers of the Year
for demonstrating excellent teaching skills,
flexibility, perseverance, patience, compassion,
and commitment to education while providing consistency
and reassurance enabling their students
to achieve academic progress
in and out of school!

Congratulations to all of our teachers!!

Please see the video links below

Retiree/25 Year https://youtu.be/EnR_8L78p9U

Teacher of the Year https://youtu.be/z8D6r_vyVWk

post_text:
***CRIME STOPPERS TIP REGARDING A THREAT TOWARDS SCHOOLS***

Around 12:30 AM, the Parsippany Police Department received an alert from the Morris County Crime Stoppers that involved threats against schools that was supposed to take place on today. This alert was also sent to several other Morris County School Districts. After an investigation by the Parsippany Police Department, it was determined that the message that was viewed on SnapChat originated from a juvenile in a school district in Bergen County. Investigating officers also determined that officers in Bergen County had also received the threat earlier on 11/5/19 and made contact with the juvenile. At no time were any Parsippany students in any danger nor did the threat mention a specific school district.

post_text:
Earlier today in the area of Woodhaven Road, an 18 year old female was approached by a well-dressed black male with a short haircut and possibly grey hair who appeared to be in his 40‚Äôs. The unknown male asked her a few questions, which included if she was in high school and if she had an older sister. The female quickly left the area.

If anyone saw the unknown male or can identify who he is, please contact our Investigative Division at 973-263-4311 or email socialmedia@parpolice.com .

Keeping our children safe is always of paramount importance. We urge you to be vigilant in making your children wary of strangers. Please let them know to tell an adult immediately if an incident occurs and to try to get a license number if at all possible. Any incident needs to be reported immediately to a responsible adult and the police should always be notified.
